Third-party code statically linked into the prebuilt libraries in this directory
================================================================================

The two binaries here —

    libtwovoip.linux.template_debug.arm64.so
    libtwovoip.linux.template_release.arm64.so

— are compiled from goatchurchprime/two-voip-godot-4 at tag v4.2 (see build-arm64.sh and
README.md), and statically link the five components below. This repository is public, so
committing these binaries is redistribution in binary form; MIT requires the copyright and
permission notice accompany all copies, and BSD-3 clause 2 requires binary redistributions
reproduce the copyright notice, conditions and disclaimer "in the documentation and/or other
materials provided with the distribution". This file is that material. Each notice below is
reproduced verbatim from the exact pinned source that was compiled.

Component        Upstream                                        Pinned at
---------        --------                                        ---------
twovoip          github.com/goatchurchprime/two-voip-godot-4     tag v4.2
godot-cpp        github.com/godotengine/godot-cpp                3dd9bf1695910f81f986df17244f0179eb671263
opus             github.com/xiph/opus                            ddbe48383984d56acd9e1ab6a090c54ca6b735a6
rnnoise          github.com/werman/noise-suppression-for-voice   9c4e5c28d8950e2cef837d8a0abd36c2fd9b5c2d
                 (subdirectory external/rnnoise only)
speex_resampler  VENDORED inside two-voip-godot-4 itself, at     tag v4.2 (tree 384af1de6a82beca798b4375f6175ad6cde0f40c)
                 src/speex_resampler/ — NOT a submodule

Enumerate the components from what the binary LINKS, not from .gitmodules — v4.2 declares only
three submodules (godot-cpp, opus, noise-suppression-for-voice), so a submodule-derived list
silently misses speex_resampler, which is vendored source in twovoip's own tree. Its object code
is in these .so: resample.c's own speex_resampler_strerror strings ("Input and output buffers
overlap.", "Unknown error. Bad error code or strange version mismatch.") are present in both.
Note also that Jean-Marc Valin appears in opus's and rnnoise's notices too, but that does not
discharge speex's — a different work's notice naming the same person is not this work's notice,
and Thorvald Natvig appears in no other component. The condition text differs materially as well
(speex clause 3 is "The name of the author may not be used..."; opus's names the Internet
Society/IETF/IETF Trust), so one cannot stand in for the other.

Not currently linked, but one bump away: src/speex_resampler/resample_neon.h and resample_sse.h
add a third holder (Copyright (C) 2011 Texas Instruments, author Jyri Sarha). They compile only
under USE_NEON / USE_SSE, which the v4.2 build never defines — verified against SConstruct — so
they are excluded today even on arm64. A future build that enables NEON must add that holder.

NOT GPL — read this before assuming otherwise
---------------------------------------------
The rnnoise code comes from the werman/noise-suppression-for-voice submodule, whose ROOT LICENSE
is GPL-3.0. That GPL-3.0 covers werman's JUCE-based VST/LV2 plugin product, which is NOT built and
NOT linked here. twovoip's SConstruct cmake-builds only the vendored `external/rnnoise`
subdirectory (BSD-3, Xiph/Valin) and links `-lRnNoise`; JUCE is never compiled. Verified against
the shipped binaries: `strings` finds zero JUCE symbols and zero GPL references in either .so, and
the rnnoise + opus symbols that are present correspond to the BSD-3 code below. If you re-run
build-arm64.sh on a future tag, re-check this before assuming it still holds.

On a version bump: regenerate the libraries with build-arm64.sh AND refresh the notices below from
the new pinned sources, so attribution stays in lockstep with the bytes.

Attribution follows the pattern of the webrtc-native addon already baked into the same image
(/opt/godot-vendor/webrtc/ ships one LICENSE.* per statically-linked dependency).


